Background

In the data folder, you will find data about shark incidents in California between 1950-2022. The data are from: State of California- Shark Incident Database.

Load the libraries

library("tidyverse")
library("janitor")

Load the data

Run the following code chunk to import the data. In this chunk, I am removing NAs.

sharks <- 
  read_csv("data/SharkIncidents_1950_2022_220302.csv", 
           na=c("NA", "N/A", "Unknown", "NOT COUNTED", "", " ")) %>% 
  clean_names()

Questions

  1. Are there any hotspots for shark incidents in California? Show the top five counties with the most incidents.
sharks %>% 
  count(county, sort=T) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% 
  slice_head(n=5)
## # A tibble: 5  2
##   county            n
##   <chr>         <int>
## 1 San Diego        25
## 2 Humboldt         20
## 3 San Mateo        19
## 4 Santa Barbara    19
## 5 Marin            16
  1. Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents per county.
sharks %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=county))+
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(fill=injury), position="dodge")+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title="Number of Incidents per County", x="County", y=NULL)

  1. Are there months of the year when incidents are more likely to occur? Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by month. Which month has the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>% 
  count(month, sort=T) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n))
## # A tibble: 12  2
##    month     n
##    <dbl> <int>

##  2     9    34

sharks %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=month, fill=injury))+
  geom_bar()+
  labs(title="Number of Incidents by Month", x="Month", y=NULL)

From the table and graph, October has the highest number of incidents.

  1. Is there a time of day when most attacks occur? Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by time of day. Which time of day has the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>% 
  select(time, injury) %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=time, fill=injury))+
  geom_bar(na.rm=T)+
  labs(title="Number of Incidents by Time of Day", x="Time of Day", y=NULL)+
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=75, hjust=1))

From the plot, shark attacks seem the most frequent around 11:00 AM.

  1. How do the number and types of injuries compare by county? Make a table that shows the number of injury types by county. Which county has the highest number incidents? (hint: your table should be in wide format)
sharks_wide <- sharks %>% 
  group_by(county, injury) %>%
  count(injury) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from="injury",
              values_from="n")

San Diego has the highest number of incidents, with most of its incidents being minor or no injuries.

  1. Use the table from #5 to make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by county.
sharks_wide %>% 
  group_by(county) %>% 
  mutate(n_incidents=sum(c(minor, none, major, `minor*`, `none*`, fatal, `major*`), na.rm=T)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=county, y=n_incidents, fill=county))+
  geom_col()+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title="Total Number of Incidents by County", x="County", y=NULL)

  1. In the data, mode refers to a type of activity. Which activity is associated with the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>% 
  count(mode, name="n_incidentsbymode") %>% 
  arrange(desc(n_incidentsbymode)) %>% 
  slice_head(n=5)
## # A tibble: 5  2

Surfing/boarding has the highest number of incidents.

  1. Make a plot that compares the number of incidents by activity.
sharks %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=mode, fill=injury))+
  geom_bar(position="dodge")+
  labs(title="Number of Incidents by Activity", x="Activity", y=NULL)+
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=30, hjust=1))

  1. Which shark species is involved in the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>% 
  count(species, name="n_incidentsbyshark") %>% 
  arrange(desc(n_incidentsbyshark)) %>% 
  slice_head(n=5)
## # A tibble: 5  2
##   species      n_incidentsbyshark
##   <chr>                     <int>
## 1 White                       181
## 2 <NA>                         14
## 3 Hammerhead                    3
## 4 Blue                          2
## 5 Killer Whale                  2

The Great White shark is involved in the highest number of incidents.

  1. Are all incidents involving Great Whites fatal? Make a plot that shows the number and types of incidents for Great Whites only.
sharks %>% 
  filter(species=="White") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=injury, fill=mode))+
  geom_bar(position="dodge")+
  labs(title="Number and Types of Incidents for Great White Sharks", x="Injury Type", y=NULL)

I originally thought fatal injuries would be the most common, but based on the data from the plot, fatal injuries are the least common (excluding none* or adding it to the regular none type). No injuries is actually the most common type for Great White shark incidents.
